  "semantics": {
    "identifierToken": "Identifier",
    "pointerToken":    "StarOp",
    "$externLibraryByFormatComment": "FF6 Slice 2 + audit fold (2026-06-02): per-format runtime library identity for source-declared externs. compileSingleUnit step 2.5 populates HirAttribute<FfiMetadata> per ExternFunction/ExternGlobal by calling synthesizeFfiFromSourceDecls() with the entry whose key matches objectFormatKindName(format.kind()). Per-LANGUAGE field (not per-declaration-rule) — the post-fold #1 placement on DeclarationRule was fragile; the pipeline first-match-loop would silently pick the wrong rule on grammars with multiple extern-shaped decl rules. Library identities: PE → msvcrt.dll (Win32 C runtime for x86_64 hello-world); ELF → libc.so.6 (glibc on Linux); Mach-O → /usr/lib/libSystem.B.dylib (libSystem dispatcher publishes the libc surface). Per-symbol overrides (`extern \"otherlib.dll\" int foo();`) anchored D-CSUBSET-EXTERN-LIBRARY-SYNTAX.",
    "externLibraryByFormat": {
      "pe":    "msvcrt.dll",
      "elf":   "libc.so.6",
      "macho": "/usr/lib/libSystem.B.dylib"
    },
    "$shippedLibDirsComment": "FF11 (2026-06-05) + Model 3 (2026-06-09): the SYSTEM include search path (C's /usr/include analogue) for the angle form `#include <h>`. A directory under src/dss-config/; the header stem maps to a language-NEUTRAL JSON descriptor (`<stem>.json`, e.g. stdio.json) read by src/ffi/shipped_lib_descriptor.cpp — its symbols (name + hir-text signature) are injected into semantic scope before Pass 2, then flow through FF5 synthesizeFfiFromSourceDecls like a program's own extern. Model 3 made each descriptor PLATFORM-NEUTRAL: ONE descriptor per header, carrying a per-object-format `library` map ({\"pe\":...,\"elf\":...,\"macho\":...}); the active compilation target's format selects its runtime image at compile_pipeline resolution (keyed via objectFormatKindName), so a SINGLE neutral directory serves every target. This DISSOLVED the former per-platform-directory selection + D-FFI-SHIPPED-LIB-PLATFORM-SELECT. The full surface (stdio/stdlib/string/ctype/math) + provenance/variadic-exclusion notes live in src/dss-config/shippedLibs/README.md.",
    "shippedLibDirs": ["shippedLibs"],
    "$pointerConversionsComment": "D-LANG-POINTER-VOID-CONVERT (step 13.2, 2026-06-02): C-standard §6.3.2.3 — `void*` converts implicitly to/from any object-pointer type without a cast. The two directions are configured INDEPENDENTLY (matching C++'s split, where only the safe direction is implicit). c-subset declares BOTH true (C-family semantics). A future C++ frontend would declare {implicitToVoidPtr: true, implicitFromVoidPtr: false} matching ISO C++ §7.11. Rust/Swift would declare both false. DEFAULT is false (struct-init); strict typing is the safety-respecting default, opposite of the Array→Ptr decay opt-out direction (which is pervasive C-family idiom; void-ptr conversion is a safety relaxation). Pointer arithmetic on void* and void*↔fn-pointer conversions are separate concerns anchored at D-LANG-VOIDPTR-ARITH-REJECT and D-LANG-VOIDPTR-FN-CONVERT respectively.",
    "pointerConversions": {
      "implicitToVoidPtr":                  true,
      "implicitFromVoidPtr":                true,
      "nullPointerConstantFromIntegerZero": true
    },
    "$pointerAliasingComment": "Two orthogonal C99-derived alias-analysis opt-ins. `strictAliasingOnDistinctTypes` (C99 §6.5): accessing an object through a pointer of an incompatible type is undefined behavior — lets the MIR optimizer's CSE/LICM Load admission prove Ptr<I32> and Ptr<I64> don't alias (Rule 6 in mirMayAlias). `charTypesAliasAll` (C99 §6.5 ¶7): character-type pointers may alias an object of any type — the canonical strict-aliasing carve-out for serializers/hash-visitors/memcpy. C-family languages declare both true. A Rust frontend or strict-typed DSL would declare `charTypesAliasAll: false` (the type-checker enforces aliasing at a higher tier). See D-OPT-LOAD-ALIAS-ANALYSIS for the substrate's design.",
    "pointerAliasing": {
      "strictAliasingOnDistinctTypes":      true,
      "charTypesAliasAll":                  true
    },
    "declarations": [
      { "rule": "varDeclHead", "name": 1, "type": 0, "kind": "variable",
        "constMarker": "ConstKeyword", "warnIfUnused": true,
        "arraySuffix": { "rule": "arrayDeclSuffix", "lengthChild": 1 } },
      { "rule": "param",       "name": 1, "type": 0, "kind": "variable",
        "constMarker": "ConstKeyword" },
      { "rule": "topLevelDecl", "name": 1, "type": 0, "kind": "variable",
        "constMarker": "ConstKeyword",
        "$linkageSpecifiersComment": "D-CSUBSET-LINKAGE-SPECIFIERS (pre-OPT7 P1): 'static' -> internal (Local) binding; '__attribute__((weak))' -> Weak. 'specifierPrefix' names the optional leading declSpecifiers rule the resolver strips before positional name/type/body resolution; 'linkageSpecifiers' maps each specifier token's SOURCE TEXT to its binding/visibility effect, stamped onto the HIR/MIR symbol so DCE preserves externally-visible symbols and elides a static-with-no-callers. Visibility (__attribute__((visibility(\"hidden\")))) is substrate-ready (facet + HIR + MIR all carry visibility) but the c-subset string-arg grammar form is deferred -- see plan 22 + the deferred-anchor registry.",
        "specifierPrefix": "declSpecifiers",
        "linkageSpecifiers": {
          "static": { "binding": "local" },
          "weak":   { "binding": "weak"  }
        },
        "linkageSpecifierIgnoredKinds": ["AttributeKeyword", "ParenOpen", "ParenClose"],
        "arraySuffix": { "rule": "arrayDeclSuffix", "lengthChild": 1 },
        "kindByChild": {
          "childPath": [2, 0],
          "whenRule": "funcDefTail",
          "whenKind": "function",
          "paramsPath": [0],
          "bodyPath":   [1]
        },
        "$implicitReturnZeroForFunctionNamesComment": "C99 §5.1.2.2.3: when control reaches the closing '}' of main without an explicit return, the semantics are equivalent to 'return 0;'. The HIR lowering appends a synthetic ReturnStmt(IntLiteral(0)) to main's body if it doesn't structurally terminate. SOURCE-AGNOSTIC: this list lives on the per-language semantic config so each language declares its own entry-fn convention (Pascal's 'program', Rust's 'fn main', etc.) without touching shared HIR substrate. Closes D-LK10-ENTRY-MAIN-IMPLICIT-RETURN.",
        "implicitReturnZeroForFunctionNames": ["main"] },
      { "rule": "typedefDecl", "name": 2, "type": 1, "kind": "type" },
      { "rule": "structDecl",  "name": 1, "kind": "type",
        "fieldChildren": { "rule": "structField", "compositeKind": "struct" } },
      { "rule": "structField", "name": 1, "type": 0, "kind": "variable" },
      { "rule": "unionDecl",   "name": 1, "kind": "type",
        "fieldChildren": { "rule": "unionField", "compositeKind": "union" } },
      { "rule": "unionField",  "name": 1, "type": 0, "kind": "variable" },
      { "rule": "enumDecl",    "name": 1, "kind": "type",
        "fieldChildren": { "rule": "enumerator", "compositeKind": "enum",
                           "liftToEnclosingScope": true } },
      { "rule": "enumerator",  "name": 0, "kind": "variable" },
      { "rule": "externDecl", "name": 2, "type": 1, "kind": "variable",
        "kindByChild": {
          "childPath": [3, 0],
          "whenRule": "externFuncTail",
          "whenKind": "function",
          "paramsPath": [1]
        },
        "variadicMarker": "EllipsisOp",
        "arraySuffix": { "rule": "arrayDeclSuffix", "lengthChild": 1 } }
    ],
    "references": [
      { "rule": "operand" },
      { "rule": "structTypeRef", "nameMatch": "lastIdentifier" },
      { "rule": "unionTypeRef",  "nameMatch": "lastIdentifier" },
      { "rule": "enumTypeRef",   "nameMatch": "lastIdentifier" }
    ],
    "memberAccesses": [
      { "rule": "postfixExpr", "lhsChild": 0, "nameChild": 2,
        "dereferences": false, "operatorToken": "DotOp"   },
      { "rule": "postfixExpr", "lhsChild": 0, "nameChild": 2,
        "dereferences": true,  "operatorToken": "ArrowOp" }
    ],
    "scopes": [ "block", "funcDefTail", "structDecl", "unionDecl", "enumDecl" ],
    "assignments": [
      { "rule": "binaryExpr", "operatorToken": "AssignOp",       "lhs": 0, "rhs": 2 },
      { "rule": "binaryExpr", "operatorToken": "PlusAssignOp",   "lhs": 0, "rhs": 2 },
      { "rule": "binaryExpr", "operatorToken": "MinusAssignOp",  "lhs": 0, "rhs": 2 },
      { "rule": "binaryExpr", "operatorToken": "StarAssignOp",   "lhs": 0, "rhs": 2 },
      { "rule": "binaryExpr", "operatorToken": "SlashAssignOp",  "lhs": 0, "rhs": 2 },
      { "rule": "binaryExpr", "operatorToken": "ModAssignOp",    "lhs": 0, "rhs": 2 },
      { "rule": "binaryExpr", "operatorToken": "BitAndAssignOp", "lhs": 0, "rhs": 2 },
      { "rule": "binaryExpr", "operatorToken": "BitOrAssignOp",  "lhs": 0, "rhs": 2 },
      { "rule": "binaryExpr", "operatorToken": "BitXorAssignOp", "lhs": 0, "rhs": 2 },
      { "rule": "binaryExpr", "operatorToken": "ShlAssignOp",    "lhs": 0, "rhs": 2 },
      { "rule": "binaryExpr", "operatorToken": "ShrAssignOp",    "lhs": 0, "rhs": 2 }
    ],
    "callRules": [
      { "rule": "postfixExpr", "callee": 0, "args": 2,
        "operatorToken": "ParenOpen" }
    ],
    "$castsComment": "FC2: explicit C cast `(T)expr`. typeChild/operandChild are visible-child indices into castExpr = [ '(' , castTypeRef , ')' , castOperand ]. Pass 2 resolves+stamps the type child (typedefs incl. cross-tree-injected ones resolve through the standard type-position resolver), stamps the cast node's RESULT type, and validates the pair against the explicit-cast matrix (scalar<->scalar incl. float<->int, ptr<->ptr, ptr<->int; struct values / void / arrays -> S_InvalidCast).",
    "casts": [
      { "rule": "castExpr", "typeChild": 1, "operandChild": 3 }
    ],
    "returnRules": [
      { "rule": "returnStmt", "value": 1 }
    ],
    "loopRules": [ "whileStmt", "forStmt", "doStmt", "switchStmt" ],
    "loopControls": [ { "rule": "breakStmt" }, { "rule": "continueStmt" } ],
    "$builtinTypesComment": "FC3 c1: the TEXT-keyed type-name table (typedef-style positions + the load-time fallback for single-word ladder/promotion names). The KEYWORD grammar path resolves through semantics.typeSpecifiers below (the C 6.7.2 multiset table) — both tables declare the SAME widths, and `long` carries the LLP64 override on BOTH so the two paths can never disagree (D-LANG-PLATFORM-DEPENDENT-PRIMITIVE-WIDTH).",
    "builtinTypes": [
      { "name": "int",    "core": "I32"  },
      { "name": "long",   "core": "I64", "coreByDataModel": { "LLP64": "I32" } },
      { "name": "char",   "core": "Char" },
      { "name": "void",   "core": "Void" },
      { "name": "bool",   "core": "Bool" },
      { "name": "float",  "core": "F32"  },
      { "name": "double", "core": "F64"  }
    ],
    "$typeSpecifiersComment": "FC3 c1: every VALID C type-specifier multiset (C 6.7.2 6) over the shipped keyword surface; combinations are ORDER-FREE (the engine canonicalizes by sorting token kinds; `long long` = LongKeyword twice). Invalid combos (`unsigned float`, `short long`, `long double`) reject by ABSENCE -> S_InvalidTypeSpecifierCombination. `long`-bearing rows carry the LLP64 (Windows) 32-bit override; `long long` stays 64-bit everywhere. NO `long double` row: F128/long-double is an FC3+ exclusion (rejects by absence).",
    "typeSpecifiers": [
      { "tokens": ["VoidKeyword"],                                              "core": "Void" },
      { "tokens": ["CharKeyword"],                                              "core": "Char" },
      { "tokens": ["SignedKeyword", "CharKeyword"],                             "core": "I8"   },
      { "tokens": ["UnsignedKeyword", "CharKeyword"],                           "core": "U8"   },
      { "tokens": ["ShortKeyword"],                                             "core": "I16"  },
      { "tokens": ["ShortKeyword", "IntKeyword"],                               "core": "I16"  },
      { "tokens": ["SignedKeyword", "ShortKeyword"],                            "core": "I16"  },
      { "tokens": ["SignedKeyword", "ShortKeyword", "IntKeyword"],              "core": "I16"  },
      { "tokens": ["UnsignedKeyword", "ShortKeyword"],                          "core": "U16"  },
      { "tokens": ["UnsignedKeyword", "ShortKeyword", "IntKeyword"],            "core": "U16"  },
      { "tokens": ["IntKeyword"],                                               "core": "I32"  },
      { "tokens": ["SignedKeyword"],                                            "core": "I32"  },
      { "tokens": ["SignedKeyword", "IntKeyword"],                              "core": "I32"  },
      { "tokens": ["UnsignedKeyword"],                                          "core": "U32"  },
      { "tokens": ["UnsignedKeyword", "IntKeyword"],                            "core": "U32"  },
      { "tokens": ["LongKeyword"],                                              "core": "I64", "coreByDataModel": { "LLP64": "I32" } },
      { "tokens": ["LongKeyword", "IntKeyword"],                                "core": "I64", "coreByDataModel": { "LLP64": "I32" } },
      { "tokens": ["SignedKeyword", "LongKeyword"],                             "core": "I64", "coreByDataModel": { "LLP64": "I32" } },
      { "tokens": ["SignedKeyword", "LongKeyword", "IntKeyword"],               "core": "I64", "coreByDataModel": { "LLP64": "I32" } },
      { "tokens": ["UnsignedKeyword", "LongKeyword"],                           "core": "U64", "coreByDataModel": { "LLP64": "U32" } },
      { "tokens": ["UnsignedKeyword", "LongKeyword", "IntKeyword"],             "core": "U64", "coreByDataModel": { "LLP64": "U32" } },
      { "tokens": ["LongKeyword", "LongKeyword"],                               "core": "I64"  },
      { "tokens": ["LongKeyword", "LongKeyword", "IntKeyword"],                 "core": "I64"  },
      { "tokens": ["SignedKeyword", "LongKeyword", "LongKeyword"],              "core": "I64"  },
      { "tokens": ["SignedKeyword", "LongKeyword", "LongKeyword", "IntKeyword"],"core": "I64"  },
      { "tokens": ["UnsignedKeyword", "LongKeyword", "LongKeyword"],            "core": "U64"  },
      { "tokens": ["UnsignedKeyword", "LongKeyword", "LongKeyword", "IntKeyword"], "core": "U64" },
      { "tokens": ["BoolKeyword"],                                              "core": "Bool" },
      { "tokens": ["LegacyBoolKeyword"],                                        "core": "Bool" },
      { "tokens": ["FloatKeyword"],                                             "core": "F32"  },
      { "tokens": ["DoubleKeyword"],                                            "core": "F64"  }
    ],
    "$literalTypesComment": "FC3 c1: IntLiteral's I32 is the BASE core; the integerLiteralTyping ladder below refines the width by magnitude/suffix/radix per C 6.4.4.1. FloatLiteral's F64 is the BASE core; the floatLiteralTyping suffix map below refines it per C 6.4.4.2 (FC3.5 sweep-c2 / D-CSUBSET-F32-CODEGEN closure: `1.5f` now types F32 — the F32 arithmetic surface shipped, so the typing flip pairs with real codegen). true/false are C23 keyword literals: type Bool with config-declared FIXED values (1/0) — the engine never decodes their text as a number.",
    "literalTypes": [
      { "literal": "IntLiteral",   "core": "I32" },
      { "literal": "FloatLiteral", "core": "F64" },
      { "literal": "TrueKeyword",  "core": "Bool", "value": 1 },
      { "literal": "FalseKeyword", "core": "Bool", "value": 0 }
    ],
    "$floatLiteralTypingComment": "FC3.5 sweep-c2: C 6.4.4.2 — a floating constant's type is keyed by its SUFFIX alone (unsuffixed -> double, f/F -> float). Type names resolve through typeSpecifiers/builtinTypes at LOAD time like the integer ladder's candidates. The loader cross-checks every numberStyle.floatSuffixes spelling is covered exactly once + an unsuffixed rule exists. C's l/L long-double suffix is NOT declared in floatSuffixes (pre-existing FC1c2 note) — long double lands with its own width story, not here.",
    "floatLiteralTyping": [
      { "suffixes": [],         "type": "double" },
      { "suffixes": ["f", "F"], "type": "float"  }
    ],
    "$integerLiteralTypingComment": "FC3 c1: C 6.4.4.1 EXACTLY — the FIRST candidate (per suffix-group x radix-class) whose range holds the decoded magnitude is the literal's type. `decimal` = no declared numberStyle prefix matched; `nondecimal` (hex/octal/binary) adds the unsigned candidates per the C table. Type names resolve through typeSpecifiers/builtinTypes at LOAD time, so LLP64's 32-bit `long` falls out of the data-model select (2147483648 is `long` on LP64 but `long long` on LLP64). Suffix GROUPS list the exact numberStyle.integerSuffixes spellings they cover; the loader cross-checks every declared suffix is covered exactly once. A magnitude beyond the last candidate -> S_IntegerLiteralTooLarge.",
    "integerLiteralTyping": [
      { "suffixes": [],
        "decimal":    ["int", "long", "long long"],
        "nondecimal": ["int", "unsigned int", "long", "unsigned long", "long long", "unsigned long long"] },
      { "suffixes": ["u", "U"],
        "decimal":    ["unsigned int", "unsigned long", "unsigned long long"],
        "nondecimal": ["unsigned int", "unsigned long", "unsigned long long"] },
      { "suffixes": ["l", "L"],
        "decimal":    ["long", "long long"],
        "nondecimal": ["long", "unsigned long", "long long", "unsigned long long"] },
      { "suffixes": ["ul", "UL", "lu", "LU"],
        "decimal":    ["unsigned long", "unsigned long long"],
        "nondecimal": ["unsigned long", "unsigned long long"] },
      { "suffixes": ["ll", "LL"],
        "decimal":    ["long long"],
        "nondecimal": ["long long", "unsigned long long"] },
      { "suffixes": ["ull", "ULL", "llu", "LLU"],
        "decimal":    ["unsigned long long"],
        "nondecimal": ["unsigned long long"] }
    ],
    "$arithmeticConversionsComment": "FC3 c1: C 6.3.1.8 usual arithmetic conversions, declared (the engine algorithm in analysis/semantic/type_rules.hpp is closed-verb config-driven; languages WITHOUT this block keep the legacy commonType path). integerPromotion: operands below `int`'s rank promote to int; `alsoPromote` pulls char/bool (outside the width-rank lattice) into promotion WITHOUT the engine hardcoding C's view of char. mixedSignedness `rank-prefer-unsigned`: unsigned rank >= signed rank -> the unsigned type, else the (strictly wider) signed type. promoteComparisons: comparisons convert operands to the common type (so -1 > 0ul compares as U64 -> true) and still yield Bool.",
    "arithmeticConversions": {
      "integerPromotion": { "minRankType": "int", "alsoPromote": ["char", "bool"] },
      "mixedSignedness": "rank-prefer-unsigned",
      "promoteComparisons": true
    }
  },

